{ We already know what happens with a single pawn. Obviously, a King with two Pawns almost always wins (95 on 100, according to our stats) . This figure would be even higher if we left aside those cases where the capture of one of the pawns is forced. We can distinguish three scenarios:

1) Connected pawns. Here both pawns defend each other and then the king approaches to give them support. The ending is always won unless a pawn is captured. The only important thing to know is this: if we have a rook's pawn on the 7th rank, we have to give it up in order to promote the knight's pawn.
2) Doubled pawns
3) Isolated pawns }
 *


